eachers for each other. The book includes one of the first biographical portraits of Teresa and Maria's personal account of the troubled founding of the Discalced convent at Seville, as well as her tribulations as an Inquisitional suspect. Rich in allusions to women's affective relationships in the early modern convent, Book for the Hour of Recreation also serves as an example of how a woman might write when relatively free of clerical censorship and expectations. A detailed introduction and notes by Alison Weber provide historical and biographical context for Amanda Powell's fluid translation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aChristian saintszSpainzAvilavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowell, Amanda.1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeber, Alison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWeber, Alison.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226734620423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226734620.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles